Story of the Week.

8
00:00:50,362 --> 00:00:57,087
$965 Billion: Anthropic Makes AI History – and Prepares for Its IPO

9
00:00:57,087 --> 00:01:08,925
Just under a trillion dollars in valuation – and still a private company: Anthropic closed a Series H funding round of $65 billion on May 28, 2026 .

10
00:01:08,925 --> 00:01:22,287
This is the largest funding round in the history of the AI sector – a signal that reframes the "AI bubble" debate, even as skeptics rightly point out that the company is still posting losses despite these figures.

11
00:01:22,287 --> 00:01:35,287
The post-money valuation of $965 billion  is backed by a consortium of Altimeter Capital, Dragoneer, Greenoaks, Sequoia, Capital Group, Coatue, and D1 Capital Partners.

12
00:01:35,287 --> 00:01:46,612
Strategic investors were far from randomly chosen: Samsung, SK Hynix, and Micron – the world's three largest chip players – are securing a seat at the table early.

13
00:01:46,612 --> 00:01:51,950
Amazon, which had already committed $5 billion in April, rounds out the picture .

14
00:01:51,950 --> 00:01:58,687
"Claude's latest advancements have driven large-scale adoption among the world's most demanding organizations."

15
00:01:58,687 --> 00:02:01,112
— Brad Gerstner, Altimeter Capital

16
00:02:01,112 --> 00:02:14,787
The underlying numbers are remarkable: Anthropic already generates an annualized run-rate revenue of over $47 billion  – with projected growth of 130% through its first profitable quarter.

17
00:02:14,787 --> 00:02:21,437
For comparison: OpenAI was valued at $852 billion in March 2026 .

18
00:02:21,437 --> 00:02:27,000
Anthropic has not only closed the gap – it is now $113 billion ahead.

19
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:33,175
For developers and enterprises, this means: Anthropic is no longer a likable underdog.

20
00:02:33,175 --> 00:02:43,650
With this capital base, the company can build its own data centers, recruit top talent from anywhere, and iterate on products that challenge OpenAI and Google as equals.

21
00:02:43,650 --> 00:02:49,250
Claude in 2026 is a serious infrastructure decision, not a lifestyle choice.

22
00:02:49,250 --> 00:02:53,512
Open Questions: When does the IPO come, and at what valuation?

23
00:02:53,512 --> 00:03:00,000
How will the market respond to a company with a $47B run rate that is still posting losses?

24
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:05,362
And: does a $1 trillion valuation force different priorities than safety research?

25
00:03:05,362 --> 00:03:19,950
Bottom Line: Valued at $965B, with its first profitable quarter in sight and the largest AI chip consortium behind it – Anthropic is 2026's heavyweight that nobody can ignore.

26
00:03:19,950 --> 00:03:21,287
More Top Stories.

27
00:03:21,287 --> 00:03:25,087
GitHub Copilot: From Flat-Rate to Usage-Based Billing.

28
00:03:25,087 --> 00:03:34,625
Starting June 1, 2026, Microsoft is billing its AI coding assistant GitHub Copilot by tokens – and developers are in shock .

29
00:03:34,625 --> 00:03:41,750
What was previously available for a monthly flat rate of ~$29 can now cost up to $750/month.

30
00:03:41,750 --> 00:03:49,475
In documented extreme cases, costs explode from ~$50 to ~$3,000/month .

31
00:03:49,475 --> 00:03:52,137
The developer community is outraged:.

32
00:03:52,137 --> 00:03:53,137
"What a joke…

33
00:03:53,137 --> 00:03:56,350
This new usage model is just stupidly expensive."

34
00:03:56,350 --> 00:03:57,537
— User on Reddit

35
00:03:57,537 --> 00:04:07,912
The real problem runs deeper: Microsoft had for years actively encouraged intensive Copilot usage – training, integrations, evangelist-driven adoption.

36
00:04:07,912 --> 00:04:14,975
The switch to token-based billing raises the question of whether the old flat-rate model simply subsidized heavy usage.

37
00:04:14,975 --> 00:04:17,762
Microsoft offered no comment by press time .

38
00:04:17,762 --> 00:04:28,575
Token-based billing is already market standard with other AI providers – the difference lies in the magnitude of the price shock for existing power users, not in the model itself.

39
00:04:28,575 --> 00:04:29,400
So What?

40
00:04:29,400 --> 00:04:41,725
Anyone using Copilot heavily must now set token budgets, actively monitor usage, and evaluate alternatives like Cursor or Windsurf in parallel – before the first monthly bill arrives.

41
00:04:41,725 --> 00:04:47,175
Microsoft's "Lethal Trifecta": Files Exfiltrated via Prompt Injection.

42
00:04:48,100 --> 00:04:56,850
A critical security vulnerability in Microsoft's Copilot "Cowork" agent allowed attackers to steal files without any user approval .

43
00:04:56,850 --> 00:05:05,737
The attack vector was alarmingly simple: manipulated messages with external images automatically triggered network requests to attacker servers.

44
00:05:05,737 --> 00:05:11,912
Through pre-authenticated download links, OneDrive files and email content were fully exfiltrable .

45
00:05:11,912 --> 00:05:28,225
Security researcher Simon Willison, who publicly documented the vulnerability, called this attack a "lethal trifecta": data access, an exfiltration path, and autonomous action without user consent – all three components combined in a single system .

46
00:05:28,225 --> 00:05:33,987
"The greatest challenge in designing agent systems is preventing attackers from exfiltrating data."

47
00:05:33,987 --> 00:05:35,200
— Simon Willison

48
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:39,287
Microsoft responded after disclosure and closed the vulnerability.

49
00:05:39,287 --> 00:05:47,937
But the incident is a wake-up call: the more autonomy an AI agent is given, the more critical security design becomes from the very start.

50
00:05:47,937 --> 00:05:48,762
So What?

51
00:05:48,762 --> 00:05:57,550
Agentic AI requires security reviews just like classical software development – and must be designed according to the principle of least privilege.

52
00:05:57,550 --> 00:06:03,037
Anyone deploying agents with file or email access should read Willison's analysis.

53
00:06:03,037 --> 00:06:09,975
Claude Opus 4.8: More Honest, Sharper, and First to Cross 10% on the Legal Benchmark.

54
00:06:09,975 --> 00:06:17,212
Simultaneous with the $65B round, Claude Opus 4.8 was released on May 28 .

55
00:06:17,212 --> 00:06:19,600
The focus of the update: honesty.

56
00:06:19,600 --> 00:06:28,912
The model not only recognizes its own mistakes better – it communicates them proactively, which makes the difference in complex, exploratory tasks.

57
00:06:28,912 --> 00:06:42,525
The technical benchmarks are clear: Opus 4.8 is approximately 4× less likely to overlook flaws in written code  – and has become the first model ever to break the 10% threshold on the Legal Agent Benchmark .

58
00:06:42,525 --> 00:06:49,350
Pricing remains constant: $5/$25 per million tokens (input/output).

59
00:06:49,350 --> 00:06:53,137
"Claude Opus 4.8 has noticeably better judgment.

60
00:06:53,137 --> 00:06:59,750
It asks the right questions, catches its own mistakes, and builds trust during complex explorations."

61
00:06:59,750 --> 00:07:01,925
— Tom Pritchard, Staff Engineer

62
00:07:01,925 --> 00:07:15,475
New features round out the release: Dynamic Workflows in Claude Code (parallelizing hundreds of subagents), Effort Control in claude.ai, and system entries in the Messages API for mid-task adjustments .

63
00:07:15,475 --> 00:07:16,300
So What?

64
00:07:16,300 --> 00:07:25,437
Dynamic Workflows alone can fundamentally accelerate agentic pipelines – this update is worth it for any team using Claude Code in production.

65
00:07:25,437 --> 00:07:26,387
